Much of the discussion on tech Twitter over the weekend has been shock that=
 a board would incinerate so much value. First off, Altman is one of the Va=
lley=E2=80=99s most-connected executives, and a prolific fund-raiser and de=
almaker; second is the fact that several OpenAI employees already resigned,=
 and more are expected to follow in the coming days. OpenAI may have had tw=
o tribes previously; it=E2=80=99s reasonable to assume that going forward i=
t will only have one, led by a new CEO in Shear who puts the probability of=
 AI doom at between 5 and 50 percent ( https://twitter.com/rowancheung/stat=
us/1726473420299534491 ) and has advocated a significant slowdown in develo=
pment ( https://twitter.com/eshear/status/1703178063306203397 ).

Here=E2=80=99s the reality of the matter, though: whether or not you agree =
with the Sutskever/Shear tribe, the board=E2=80=99s charter and responsibil=
ity is not to make money. This is not a for-profit corporation with a fiduc=
iary duty to its shareholders; indeed, as I laid out above, OpenAI=E2=80=99=
s charter specifically states that it is =E2=80=9Cunconstrained by a need t=
o generate financial return=E2=80=9D. From that perspective the board is in=
 fact doing its job, as counterintuitive as that may seem: to the extent th=
e board believes that Altman and his tribe were not =E2=80=9Cbuild[ing] gen=
eral-purpose artificial intelligence that benefits humanity=E2=80=9D it is =
empowered to fire him; they do, and so they did.

My conclusion in that Article =E2=80=94 which was published before Altman m=
ostly won the power struggle =E2=80=94 is that the non-profit structure act=
ually compromised OpenAI=E2=80=99s stated goals, which would have been bett=
er served with a traditional corporate structure:

The counter to the argument I just put forth about Microsoft=E2=80=99s poor=
 decision to partner with a non-profit is the reality of AI development, sp=
ecifically the need for massive amounts of compute. It was the need for thi=
s compute that led OpenAI, which had barred itself from making a traditiona=
l venture capital deal, to surrender their IP to Microsoft in exchange for =
Azure credits. In other words, while the board may have had the charter of =
a non-profit, and an admirable willingness to act on and stick to their con=
victions, they ultimately had no leverage because they weren=E2=80=99t a fo=
r-profit company with the capital to be truly independent.

All of this trouble, from last year=E2=80=99s board fight to this lawsuit, =
could have been avoided if OpenAI were simply a normal company. And yet, th=
e argument goes, OpenAI would have never gotten off the ground or recruited=
 the talent it did if it were anything but a non-profit. How is that an exc=
use, though? To put it another way, the true founding principle of OpenAI w=
as, at least if we look at outcomes, deception, both of the public and of O=
penAI=E2=80=99s initial staff and, at least according to Musk, it=E2=80=99s=
 initial funder. It may pass legal muster, but it doesn=E2=80=99t seem idea=
l that the very foundations of the entity seeking to create god-like powers=
 isn=E2=80=99t exactly trustworthy.

